    "recap_url": "https://www.godeacs.com/news/2026/3/21/baseball-no-24-wake-forest-evens-series-with-no-9-virginia-behind-big-third-inning",
    "recap_headline": "Wake Forest Athletics",
    "recap_text": "CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. \u2013\nBehind an eight-run third inning that featured six, two-out RBIs, the No. 24 Wake Forest baseball team (17-6, 4-4 ACC) evened the series at a game apiece with No. 9 Virginia (19-5, 5-3 ACC), taking game two of the series 13-4 on Saturday afternoon at Disharoon Park.\nSeven different Wake Forest hitters drove in a run, led by three RBIs from freshman\nJD Stein\nand two RBIs each from juniors\nKade Lewis\nand\nJavar Williams\n. Additionally, the Demon Deacons pounded out a season-high 16 hits, with seven going for extra bases.\nStein mashed his first career home run, sending a 362-foot two-run blast deep into the left field bleachers. The Carmel, Ind., native finished the game with a pair of hits, tying his career high with a trio of RBIs.\nWilliams continued to see the ball well with a 3-for-4 day, including his fifth home run of the year to open the scoring for Wake Forest. Williams also roped a double down the line in right field and drove in his second run of the day with a bases-loaded walk in the third inning.\nMaking his first start as a Demon Deacon, left fielder\nBoston Torres\nshowed out in his home state, finishing the contest with a trio of hits, including an RBI double in the fourth inning, a pair of singles and a walk.\nJunior second baseman\nBlake Schaaf\nlogged his first three-hit performance as a Demon Deacon, finishing a home run shy of the cycle.\nStarting pitcher\nChris Levonas\npicked up his fifth win of the season on the mound, tossing 5.0 innings, allowing two earned runs on four hits and striking out five. The sophomore entered the game leading the nation in strikeouts per nine innings, and now sits at 16.4 K/9 with 56 punchouts in 30.2 innings pitched.\nSenior\nZach Johnston\nrecorded the final four outs on the mound for the Demon Deacons, with all four outs coming via the strikeout to preserve the victory.\nHOW IT HAPPENED\nDespite a leadoff single by junior center fielder\nJavar Williams\n, the Demon Deacons were unable to strike in the top of the first.\nWorking around a two-out walk, starting pitcher\nChris Levonas\nput up a zero, including his first strikeout of the afternoon.\nVirginia grabbed a 1-0 lead in the bottom of the second on a Wake Forest miscue.\nThe Demon Deacons responded immediately with eight runs in the top of the third.\nWilliams stayed red hot, blasting his fifth home run of the year over the wall in left to tie the contest at 1-1.\nAfter a walk and a stolen base from first baseman\nKade Lewis\n, sophomore\nDalton Wentz\nlasered a double 111 mph off the bat to plate Lewis and give Wake Forest the lead.\nFighting off a 1-2 pitch, designated hitter\nMatt Conte\npoked a single to center to drive in Wentz and stretch the Deacs' advantage.\nLeft fielder\nBoston Torres\nroped a double into the gap in left-center to plate Conte and make it 4-1.\nBack-to-back bases-loaded walks to shortstop\nJD Stein\nand Williams plated two more.\nLewis laced a two-RBI single to left field to cap the scoring, as the Demon Deacons scored six of their eight runs in the inning with two away.\nA solo home run got a run back for the Cavaliers in the bottom of the third.\nVirginia cut the Wake lead to 8-3 with a run in the bottom of the fourth.\nWake Forest loaded the bases in the fifth but was unable to add on to its advantage.\nLevonas worked a clean frame in his final inning of work to keep Wake's lead at 8-3 after five complete innings.\nSophomore reliever\nNate Whysong\nentered in the sixth and made quick work of the Hoos, picking up a pair of strikeouts in the frame.\nThe Demon Deacons tacked on two more on a bases-loaded walk and a wild pitch to stretch the lead to 10-3 in the seventh.\nSophomore\nRhys Bowie\nentered with the bases juiced in the bottom of the seventh, escaping the jam with a groundout to short to keep the lead at seven through seven.\nAfter a leadoff triple by second baseman\nBlake Schaaf\ndown the right field line, Stein launched his first career home run deep into the bleachers in right field to push the lead out to 12-3 in the top of the eighth.\nA solo homer got a run back for UVA in the bottom half of the inning.\nCatcher\nJimmy Keenan\nadded an RBI single in the ninth to stretch the lead to nine.\nSenior\nZach Johnston\nworked a clean bottom of the ninth to cap the 13-4 victory and even the series.\nIN THE SPOTLIGHT\nJunior\nJavar Williams\nhas been phenomenal in his five career games played at Disharoon Park, going 13-for-25 (.520) with three doubles and a home run. The Dartmouth, Mass., native has also scored eight times while driving in five runs.\nWilliams continues to tear up conference pitching, as he is 18-for-33 (.545) with eight RBIs, four home runs and a trio of doubles in ACC play.\nSTAGGERING STATISTICS\nThe Demon Deacons move to 10-0 this season when scoring 10 or more runs, and are 210-15 in such games in 17 seasons under head coach\nTom Walter\n.\nFROM COACH WALTER\n\"That's a great win. We needed it.\nChris Levonas\nclutched up for us. His pitch count was high at about 48 pitches through two innings. I was worried we wouldn't be able to get five out of him, but we had a quick 12-pitch third inning, which was huge. He managed to gut it out in the fourth and the fifth and get three big outs in a big situation.\nJD Stein\nmakes that big play to end the fifth. Offensively, we finally put some timely hitting together in that third inning where we exploded. We got some big two-out RBIs from [Boston] Torres and\nKade Lewis\n. I'm really pleased with our offensive effort today. We haven't used\nEvan Jones\nyet, or\nWill Ray\n, or\nTroy Dressler\n, so we feel good going into tomorrow. It's a big game and we need to find a way to get a series win on the road.\" - Head Coach\nTom Walter\nUP NEXT\nThe Demon Deacons and Cavaliers square off in the rubber game of the series tomorrow, Mar. 22, at 1 p.m. ET on the ACC Network.\nFOLLOW THE DEACS\nGoDeacs.com\n|\nTwitter\n|\nInstagram\n|\nFacebook",
